It was a pleasure and honor to have this hands-on learning experience with this new technology.

I added my human touch, enhancing the work with hand-drawn layers. In a collaboration between human and machine, her spirit embodies the beauty of both worlds.

that we face everyday.

This piece is the first time I have used AI in my artwork. I was fortunate to be trained by an AI engineer, James, who taught me how to create training sets from scratch, run trained text to img & img to img models, and of course how to write prompts

In Her, we all see different things: a reflection of ourselves or those around us, inspiring us to tap into our own potential & lead the way to balance, love, or the next challenge. When I look at Her, I see my own journey as an artist, creator, builder & the struggles & triumphs

Wrapped in ribbons with an introspective gaze, she is a symbol of balance, energy, life, power, and beauty in the world. 

The title "Her" is a nod to the ideal that many creatives like myself strive for: a state of flow where the world melts away and we are one with the muse.

I had the honor of working with @eli_schein and the @proof_xyz team to release Grails work #2 on season III

This is the first time I have ever incorporated AI into my work and I couldn't think of a better way to release "Her".

It's been a big jump for me going from an artist/creative to a business leader, but I'm learning as I go and feeling proud of what I've accomplished. 

What is the biggest thing you learned this past year that you are going to apply to your professional life in 2023?

It's been disheartening because I never experienced the â€œwomanâ€ in business hurdles even when I worked in industries that are notoriously the worst for women (finance). I regret thinking that people just needed thicker skin. There is definitely truth behind the stories.

I know you may roll your eyes at this one. Regrettably, I have in the past too.
This year I've experienced firsthand the lack of respect that can come w/ being a woman in business. I've had terrible experiences w/ 3rd parties who treated me like dirt bc they saw me as weak.

I learned to listen more than you talk.  Learn from everyone.  Learn from your team, learn from people that have had huge success, learn people that have had crushing failures. Listening and understanding will take you far.

Oh but one note from the lesson above... there is a rigged system. You have to know that most of the other businesses around you are playing the game. Paid shills, purchased followers, false hype, straight up sharks.

You have to decide what you are willing or not willing to do.

I learned the importance of marketing. You can build the best product or service out there, but if you're not shouting from the rooftops about it, no one will know. This one is still a work in progress, but you will see a lot more of me :)

As the founder, it's important to only focus on the things that only you can do. (I'm still working on this!)

The 85% rule: if someone else on the team can do something 85% as well as you can, let them take the lead. Only do what only you can do so that you can grow the business

I learned that building a team of A players is exceptionally hard. It takes forever to find people with skill, passion, and drive but that extra time and effort is ALWAYS worth it.

The wrong people can be a huge detriment to your company.
Starting my own business has been a rollercoaster of terror, joy, learning, and every other emotion in the book

From artist to CEO: my journey and the lessons I learned in one year

The color variants of â€œDonâ€™t Feed the Pigeonsâ€ are all named after graffiti, stickers, or signs found in New York. 

There is a special nod hidden in the SVG layers to a very special friend, R.I.P. @money_alotta, love from all of the beautiful creatures here missing you.
As the many signs read â€œDonâ€™t Feed the Pigeonsâ€, or do, but at least stop to appreciate the beautiful life - big and small - that creates the beating pulse of New York City.

Over the years, like a true New Yorker, they have scrappily adapted to their new environment, thriving in a concrete jungle built for mankind. Despite their fall in status, they are still as intertwined with the city as Lady Liberty.

Some kept as pets, some used as mail carriers with their intelligence & navigational skills, others decorated w/ medals of honor for saving thousands of lives in war or stranded boats out at sea. In fact, pigeons were brought to America on the first-ever expeditions from Europe.

Pigeons have a bad rep. Sure, people see them as pests now, but starting even earlier than 4500 BCE (6,500 years ago), it was a different story. Once considered a beautiful companion, pigeons were highly respected creatures.

Hustling down a New York City street, under a sea of towering skyscrapers & kaleidoscopes of light, a gust of air rushes through your hair as a dozen pigeons take flight around you. Their silvery gray feathers glow blue, red, & purple from the hues above. Donâ€™t they look regal?
